04113nam a22007335i 9780823279708DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232797087 a10.1515/97808232797082doi  a(DE-B1597)555148  a(OCoLC)1029605493  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0130002bisacsh04a1842231 aNaas, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlato and the Invention of Life /cMichael Naas. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Philosophy's Gigantomachia over Life and Being -- tchapter 1. The Lifelines of the Statesman -- tchapter 2. Life and Spontaneity -- tchapter 3. The Shepherd and the Weaver: A Foucauldian Fable -- tchapter 4. The Mea sure of Life and Logos -- tchapter 5. Fruits of the Poisonous Tree: Plato and Alcidamas on the Evils of Writing -- tchapter 6. The Life of Law and the Law of Life -- tchapter 7. Plato and the Invention of Life Itself -- tConclusion: Life on the Line -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe question of life, Michael Naas argues, though rarely foregrounded by Plato, runs through and structures his thought. By characterizing being in terms of life, Plato in many of his later dialogues, including the Statesman, begins to discover-or, better, to invent-a notion of true or real life that would be opposed to all merely biological or animal life, a form of life that would be more valuable than everything we call life and every life that can actually be lived.This emphasis on life in the Platonic dialogues illuminates the structural relationship between many of Plato's most time-honored distinctions, such as being and becoming, soul and body. At the same time, it helps to explain the enormous power and authority that Plato's thought has exercised, for good or ill, over our entire philosophical and religious tradition.Lucid yet sophisticated, Naas's account offers a fundamental rereading of what the concept of life entails, one that inflects a range of contemporary conversations, from biopolitics, to the new materialisms, to the place of the human within the living world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aLife. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Metaphysics.2bisacsh  aBare life.  aBiopower.  aJacques Derrida.  aLife.  aMyth.  aOntology.  aPlato.  aStatesmanship.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072900940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823279708zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823279708423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823279708.jpg  a978-3-11-072900-9  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK